  <section id="erm-early-life">
    <h4>Early Life in Williamson County, Tennessee</h4>
    <p>
      Edwin Richard Myrick first appears in the 1850 U.S. Census in Williamson County, Tennessee,
      in a household headed by the Swanson family. In that enumeration, <strong>Mary Myrick (age 42)</strong>
      and <strong>Edwin R. Myrick (age 18)</strong> are listed together, with Edwin described as a farmer.
      The same household also includes Mary E. Swanson and young children, indicating a blended family structure.
    </p>

    <p>
      A probate entry later clarifies the family relationships directly. In <strong>Will Book #12, Page 271 (Nov. 1856)</strong>,
      <strong>Mary Myrick West</strong> identifies her two children as <strong>Edwin R. Myrick</strong> and
      <strong>Mary E. Swanson, wife of Ira Swanson</strong>.
      This record is a key statement tying Edwin to Mary Myrick (later West) and connecting him to his half-sister.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="erm-marriage-migration">
    <h4>Marriage and Move to Texas</h4>
    <p>
      Edwin married <strong>Mary E. Nicholson</strong> on <strong>September 30, 1856</strong> in Williamson County, Tennessee.
      Not long after, the couple joined the westward migration into Texas that drew many Middle Tennessee families during this period.
    </p>

    <p>
      By the <strong>1860 U.S. Census</strong>, Edwin and Mary are enumerated in <strong>Collin County, Texas</strong>.
      Edwin appears as <strong>E. R. Myeck/Myrick</strong> (spelling variant), age 27, with occupation listed as
      <strong>Physician</strong>. The household includes <strong>Mary E.</strong> (age 20) and their daughter
      <strong>Rosa E.</strong> (age 1), born in Texas—evidence the family had established itself in Texas by 1859.
    </p>
  </section>

